commits.message:
GH-987 Add /near command  (#1111)

* Add /near command

 - implement Near command with Entity-Overview, Entity-Highliting and radius-option

* Adapted /near command to Jakubk15 suggestions
 - The near command without any arguments does only show players.
 - Entity Scopes were added to view specified groups of entities (e.g. all living entities, all hostile ones...)
 - the glow effect is exclusively displayed when players with a specific permission use the command.
 - to handle the permission checking better, the permissions are now stored in NearPermissionConstant.java.

* Diverse small enhancements
 - Replaced the usage of minecraftScheduler.java with minecraftScheduler.java.
 - Removed the 'feature' middle part of the permission
 - Extracted the building of the entity list string into an own (inner) class to increase readability and extensibility

* Update polish translation

Co-authored-by: Jakub KÄ™dziora <77227023+Jakubk15@users.noreply.github.com>

* Update according to suggestions

* Add polish translations

* Simplify code, standardize entry sending.

* Don't use enum

* Fix messages

* Switch scope for `mob` type. Fix translations to better describe placeholders

* Added GlowingEntities api, refactor glow entity to show only for the player who executed command

---------

# Pull Request title

It should be in the following format:

```
gh-NNNNNN: Summary of the changes made
```

Where: gh-NNNNNN refers to the GitHub issue number.

Most PRs will require an issue number. Trivial changes, like fixing a typo, do not need an issue.

# Backport Pull Request title

If this is a backport PR (PR made against branches other than `main`),
please ensure that the PR title is in the following format:

```
[X.Y] <title from the original PR> (GH-NNNNNN)
```

Where: [X.Y] is the branch name, for example: [3.13].

GH-NNNNNN refers to the PR number from `main`.

-->

pull_request.title: Add support for parse_url in ANSI mode
pull_request.body:
This contributes to https://github.com/NVIDIA/spark-rapids/issues/11193.  This adds ANSI mode support to the ParseURI JNI functions, providing the foundational layer needed to implement Spark's `parse_url` function with ANSI compliance in the spark-rapids plugin.

### Changes Made

####  **Added ANSI Mode Support to JNI Layer**
- **Java Layer**: Added `failOnError` parameter to all `ParseURI` JNI methods (`parseURIProtocol`, `parseURIHost`, `parseURIQuery`, `parseURIPath`)
- **C++ Layer**: Implemented `parse_uri_ansi()` function that throws exceptions for invalid URIs in ANSI mode
- **JNI Bindings**: Updated all native method signatures to support ANSI mode parameter

####  **Tests**
- Added ANSI mode tests verifying exception throwing behavior
- Added tests for missing query parameters (should return `NULL`, not throw exceptions)
- Added tests in both cpp and java.

#### ANSI Mode Behavior
- **`failOnError = false`**: Returns `NULL` for invalid URLs (standard behavior)
- **`failOnError = true`**: Throws `exception_with_row_index` for structurally invalid URLs (ANSI mode)
- **Missing query parameters**: Return `NULL` in both modes (not considered invalid URLs)
- **NULL inputs**: Always return `NULL` in both modes

pull_request.title: Add support for parse_url in ANSI mode
pull_request.body:
This contributes to https://github.com/NVIDIA/spark-rapids/issues/11193.  This adds ANSI mode support to the ParseURI JNI functions, providing the foundational layer needed to implement Spark's `parse_url` function with ANSI compliance in the spark-rapids plugin.

### Changes Made

####  **Added ANSI Mode Support to JNI Layer**
- **Java Layer**: Added `failOnError` parameter to all `ParseURI` JNI methods (`parseURIProtocol`, `parseURIHost`, `parseURIQuery`, `parseURIPath`)
- **C++ Layer**: Implemented `parse_uri_ansi()` function that throws exceptions for invalid URIs in ANSI mode
- **JNI Bindings**: Updated all native method signatures to support ANSI mode parameter

####  **Tests**
- Added ANSI mode tests verifying exception throwing behavior
- Added tests for missing query parameters (should return `NULL`, not throw exceptions)
- Added tests in both cpp and java.

#### ANSI Mode Behavior
- **`failOnError = false`**: Returns `NULL` for invalid URLs (standard behavior)
- **`failOnError = true`**: Throws `exception_with_row_index` for structurally invalid URLs (ANSI mode)
- **Missing query parameters**: Return `NULL` in both modes (not considered invalid URLs)
- **NULL inputs**: Always return `NULL` in both modes

This Issue is about a test that "flakes", that is, it fails intermittently.

Study the RSpec Matchers [contain_exactly](https://rspec.info/features/3-13/rspec-expectations/built-in-matchers/contain-exactly/), [match_array](https://rspec.info/features/3-13/rspec-expectations/built-in-matchers/) and figure out a way.

pull_request.body:
Bumps [react-pdf](https://github.com/wojtekmaj/react-pdf/tree/HEAD/packages/react-pdf) from 9.2.1 to 10.1.0.
Release notes

Sourced from react-pdf's releases.

v10.1.0

What's new?

  • Added support for functions as children. React-PDF has never been simpler to work with! Say goodbye toonLoadSuccess, say goodbye to setting number of pages in your own state, say goodbye to extra renders! Now, rendering a simple document is as trivial as: 
    <Document file="sample.pdf">
  {({ pdf }) => Array(pdf.numPages)
    .fill(null)
    .map((_, index) => <Page key={index} pageIndex={index} />
  ))}
</Document>
    Thanks @â€‹adamaoc for inspiration!
  • Updated PDF.js to 5.3.93.
  • Updated documentation on JPEG 2000 support.
  • Updated dependencies.
  • Exported LinkService type for convenience.

What's changed?

  • usePageContext will now provide non-null value sooner than before, before the page is actually loaded. This is uniform with how useDocumentContext behaves and with how types were designed from the start, so you should not be affected by this change.
  • React-PDF now targets es2018 and not es2017. PDF.js, our core dependency, already used modern JavaScript syntax, so you should not be affected by this change.

v10.0.1

Bug fixes

  • Fixed commonly used types not reexported.

v10.0.0

See Upgrade guide from version 9.x to 10.x.

After more than a year since our last major release, we're thrilled to bring you React-PDF 10.

This update includes a major PDF.js upgrade, new features to make your life easier, improved stability, and some important breaking changes.

ðŸ‘€ Want to see exciting features more often? Consider sponsoring React-PDF.

â—ï¸ = breaking change

What's new?

  • â—ï¸ Dropped CommonJS build, making the package ESM-only. Chances are you're not going to be affected by this change at all, as all common bundlers support ESM out of the box.
    • However, you may encounter issues running unit tests using Jest. Consider migrating to Vitest.
  • Updated PDF.js to 5.3.31.
    • Performance boosts: Key rendering routines refactored to cut memory usage and speed up page loading.
    • JPEG2000 downscaling: Automatic downscale of large JPEG2000 images during decoding to improve render times.
    • CMYK JPEG fix: Correct handling of the alpha channel when WebAssembly is disabled.
    • Viewer stability: Better handling of missing/invalid Content-Range headers.
    • API cleanup: Removed deprecated options, adopted parameter objects for core methods, and introduced private class fields for cleaner code.
  • Added support for scale prop in Document component, allowing you to set the scale for the entire document.

... (truncated)

- This change enhances debugging capabilities by providing more comprehensive information about real-time and scheduled times for specified stops.

feat: add branches and checkout commands

Add a 'g' group for git commands to the application, within this
there are two new commands: branches, and co.

The branches command shows the branches available in the current
repository, and optionally searches them. The search is very basic
just checking for the search string within the branch name.

The co command uses the same logic as above, you can enter a branch
name that you'd like to checkout and it will search branches for a
match. If there is only one match, it will just check it out. If
there are multiple matches, then it will present an interactive
choice where you can use the TUI to select which branch you actually
want.

To implement the choices TUI, I used the bubbletea package. This
handles the interactivity for the app.

To implement the git commands, it is using the exec package, but i
introduced a service within the hostsys package to abstract this a
bit and avoid some duplication each time we need to call execute a
tool in the system.

While doing this I also introduced a logging package that we can use
to configure log levels throughout the app. As most of this is a
kind of TUI, the errors are presented anyway so the log level by
default is a custom "none" level that won't show anything. This log
level is a persistent flag that can be changed on each command and
will show more errors if needed for debugging.

issue.title: Feature Request: Favorite Locations with Daily Recommendations
issue.body:
**Description:**
Currently, after login or registration, users are redirected to the homepage.
I propose adding a "Choose Favorite Locations" step where users can select up to 3 favorite destinations.

**Proposed Flow:**

After login/register, redirect users to a "Choose Favorite Locations" page.

Allow users to select at most 3 destinations.

Store these preferences in the userâ€™s profile (MongoDB).

On subsequent visits, when the user opens the app, show a daily recommended location from their favorites as a notification/banner.

**Benefits:**

Increases personalization of the app.

Makes the travel experience more engaging.

Encourages users to explore their favorite locations.
